# App Router Patterns

## App Router Patterns
- Use App Router (Next.js 14+); no Pages Router patterns.
- Server Components by default; add "use client" only when needed.
- Layout files (`layout.tsx`) for shared UI structure.
- Page files (`page.tsx`) for route-specific content.

## Client vs Server
- Server Components: data fetching, static content, SEO.
- Client Components: interactivity, hooks, browser APIs, animations.
- Keep data fetching in Server Components when possible.
- Use client components for forms, modals, and interactive features.

## Routing
- File-based routing in `app/` directory.
- Use `next/navigation` for client-side navigation (`useRouter`, `usePathname`).
- Dynamic routes with `[param]` folders.
- Route groups with `(group)` folders for organization without affecting URLs.

## Data Fetching
- Use async Server Components for data fetching (no `getServerSideProps`).
- Client-side data fetching in Client Components with hooks.
- Prefer loading states with `loading.tsx` files.
- Use error boundaries with `error.tsx` files.

## Do
- Default to Server Components.
- Use Client Components only for interactivity.
- Leverage Next.js built-in optimizations (Image, Font, etc.).
- Keep route logic in page files, not in components.

## Don't
- Use Pages Router patterns (`getServerSideProps`, `getStaticProps`).
- Mix server and client code in same component without clear boundaries.
- Fetch data in Client Components when Server Components can do it.
- Use `useEffect` for data fetching in Server Components.

